39":"1186–1239","1197–1249":"1197–1249","environ 1245":"about 1245","1197":"1197","1186":"1186","1230":"1230","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","1239":"1239","1249":"1249","1346":"1346","1289":"1289","1245":"1245","1265":"1265","1229":"1229","Brittany, France":"Brittany, France","Courcy, Calvados, Normandie, France":"Courcy, Calvados, Normandy, France","Brucourt, Calvados, Normandie, France":"Brucourt, Calvados, Normandy, France","Courcy, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Courcy, Calvados, Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Courcy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alphonse, Andree, Jacques, Michel, Monique.","French: habitational name from any of the places in Calvados, Loiret, Manche, and Marne called Courcy.","History: Nicolas Lemière <i>dit</i> Courcy from Courcy in Manche, France, married Louise-Geneviève Dubé in Rivière-Ouelle, QC, in 1749."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Gillaume","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>William</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]},{"name":"III","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Japanese Yuko, Aiko, Hideaki, Hiroki, Hiroyuki, Isamu, Kaoru, Katsumi, Keiichiro, Kenji, Masako, Masayuki.","Japanese: variously written, sometimes with characters used phonetically; the most probable meanings are 仁井 ‘benevolent well’, 新居 ‘new residence’, or 新井 ‘new well’. It is not common in Japan."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Baron Gillaume III de Courcy was born in 1229, in Courcy, Calvados, Normandy, France, his father, Robert IV de Courcy - Baron de Courcy, was 43 and his mother, Mathilde de Houdetot, was 32. He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Anne de Marigny. He died in 1289, in his hometown, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1229–1289":"1229–1289","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","1245–1280":"1245–1280","1265–1346":"1265–1346","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1186–1239":"1186–1239","1197–1249":"1197–1249","environ 1245":"umbes 1245","1197":"1197","1186":"1186","1230":"1230","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","1239":"1239","1249":"1249","1346":"1346","1289":"1289","1245":"1245","1265":"1265","1229":"1229","Brittany, France":"Bretagne, Prantsusmaa","Courcy, Calvados, Normandie, France":"Courcy, Calvados, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Brucourt, Calvados, Normandie, France":"Brucourt, Calvados, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Courcy, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Courcy, Calvados, Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1229–1289":"122